"Implement the following plan:\n\n# Detect External Hook Managers and Warn Users\n\n## Context\n\nPR #355 fixed hook installation to use `git rev-parse --git-path hooks`, which correctly resolves `core.hooksPath` (e.g., Husky's `.husky/_/`). However, Husky regenerates `.husky/_/` on every `npm install` (via the `prepare` script), so Entire's hooks get overwritten.\n\n**Goal:** Detect when an external hook manager is in use, warn the user during `entire enable`, and provide copy-paste instructions for a durable integration.\n\n## New Files\n\n### `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/hook_managers.go`\n\n**Data model:**\n```go\ntype HookManager struct {\n    Name       string // \"Husky\", \"Lefthook\", \"pre-commit\", \"Overcommit\"\n    ConfigPath string // relative path that triggered detection (e.g., \".husky/\")\n    OverwritesHooks bool // true if tool will overwrite Entire's hooks on reinstall\n}\n```\n\n**Detection function:**\n```go\nfunc DetectHookManagers(repoRoot string) []HookManager\n```\n\nDetection is filesystem-only (no git commands, no file reads — just `os.Stat`):\n\n| Manager | Signal | `OverwritesHooks` |\n|---------|--------|-------------------|\n| Husky v9+ | `.husky/_/` directory exists | `true` |\n| Lefthook | `lefthook.yml` or `.lefthook.yml` exists | `false` |\n| pre-commit | `.pre-commit-config.yaml` exists | `false` |\n| Overcommit | `.overcommit.yml` exists | `false` |\n\nReturns a slice (repos can have multiple managers, e.g., Husky + lint-staged config).\n\n**Warning generation:**\n```go\nfunc HookManagerWarning(managers []HookManager, cmdPrefix string) string\n```\n\nBuilds warning text from `buildHookSpecs(cmdPrefix)` via an `extractCommandLine()` helper — this keeps the copy-paste instructions always in sync with actual hook content.\n\n**Public entry point (called from setup.go):**\n```go\nfunc CheckAndWarnHookManagers(w io.Writer) []HookManager\n```\n\nCalls `paths.RepoRoot()`, `DetectHookManagers()`, writes warning to `w`, returns detected managers.\n\n### `cmd/entire/cli/strategy/hook_managers_test.go`\n\nTests:\n- `TestDetectHookManagers_None` — clean repo\n- `TestDetectHookManagers_Husky` — `.husky/_/` present\n- `TestDetectHookManagers_Lefthook` — `lefthook.yml` present\n- `TestDetectHookManagers_PreCommit` — `.pre-commit-config.yaml` present\n- `TestDetectHookManagers_Overcommit` — `.overcommit.yml` present\n- `TestDetectHookManagers_Multiple` — multiple managers\n- `TestHookManagerWarning_Husky` — verifies Husky warning includes all 4 hook commands\n- `TestHookManagerWarning_GitHooksManager` — verifies Category B message\n- `TestExtractCommandLine` — unit test for the helper\n\nAll tests use `t.Parallel()` + `t.TempDir()`.\n\n## Modified Files\n\n### `cmd/entire/cli/setup.go` — 4 call sites\n\nAdd `strategy.CheckAndWarnHookManagers(w)` after each `InstallGitHook()` call:\n\n1. **Line 306** — `runEnableWithStrategy()`\n2. **Line 404** — `runEnableInteractive()`\n3. **Line 614** — `setupAgentHooksNonInteractive()`\n4. **Line 715** — `setupGitHook()` (uses `os.Stderr` since this function has no `w` param)\n\nPattern:\n```go\nif _, err := strategy.InstallGitHook(true); err != nil {\n    return fmt.Errorf(\"failed to install git hooks: %w\", err)\n}\nstrategy.CheckAndWarnHookManagers(w) // NEW\n```\n\nThe warning only prints during `entire enable`, never during EnsureSetup self-healing (which calls `InstallGitHook(true)` directly without `CheckAndWarnHookManagers`).\n\n## Warning Messages\n\n**Husky (overwrites hooks):**\n```\nWarning: Husky detected (.husky/)\n\n  Husky may overwrite hooks installed by Entire on npm install.\n  To make Entire hooks permanent, add these lines to your Husky hook files:\n\n    .husky/prepare-commit-msg:\n      entire hooks git prepare-commit-msg \"$1\" \"$2\" 2>/dev/null || true\n\n    .husky/commit-msg:\n      entire hooks git commit-msg \"$1\" || exit 1\n\n    .husky/post-commit:\n      entire hooks git post-commit 2>/dev/null || true\n\n    .husky/pre-push:\n      entire hooks git pre-push \"$1\" || true\n```\n\n**Category B tools (backup/chain works, but may need re-enable):**\n```\nNote: Lefthook detected (lefthook.yml)\n\n  If Lefthook reinstalls hooks, run 'entire enable' to restore Entire's hooks.\n```\n\n## Verification\n\n1. `mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test:ci`\n2. Manual test: create a temp repo with `.husky/_/` dir, run `entire enable`, verify warning appears\n3. Manual test: create a temp repo with `lefthook.yml`, verify note appears\n4. Manual test: clean repo without hook managers, verify no warning\n\n\nIf you need specific details from before exiting plan mode (like exact code snippets, error messages, or content you generated), read the full transcript at: /Users/robin/.REDACTED.jsonl\n\n---\n\ncommit this\n\n---\n\n[Request interrupted by user for tool use]\n\n---\n\nmove to another branch before committing\n\n---\n\nlets run the manual tests\n\n---\n\nLefthook looks for a configuration file using the pattern {.,}lefthook.{yml,yaml,json,toml} DeepWiki. So all valid main config files are:\n\nlefthook.yml\nlefthook.yaml\nlefthook.json\nlefthook.toml\n.lefthook.yml\n.lefthook.yaml\n.lefthook.json\n.lefthook.toml\n\nPlus the local override variants (same pattern with -local):\n\nlefthook-local.yml / .lefthook-local.yml (and .yaml, .json, .toml)\n\n---\n\nwhy is HookManager and DetectHookManagers exported (capitalized)?\n\n---\n\nefthook is the most flexible in terms of config file naming. During installation, Lefthook looks for a configuration file using the pattern {.,}lefthook.{yml,yaml,json,toml} DeepWiki. So all valid main config files are:\n\nlefthook.yml\nlefthook.yaml\nlefthook.json\nlefthook.toml\n.lefthook.yml\n.lefthook.yaml\n.lefthook.json\n.lefthook.toml\n\nPlus the local override variants (same pattern with -local):\n\nlefthook-local.yml / .lefthook-local.yml (and .yaml, .json, .toml)\n\n---\n\nlet make HookManager and DetectHookManagers local (not captialised)\n\n---\n\n/reviewer\n\n---\n\ncreate a PR\n\n---\n\ninitGitRepo duplicates the existing initHooksTestRepo helper in hooks_test.go (both run git init, t.Chdir, and clear the RepoRoot cache). Reusing the shared helper would reduce duplication and keep repo setup logic consistent across tests."